    "title": "AI & Robotics Snacks — April 30, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-30",
    "tags": ["OpenAI o3", "GPT-4.1", "Llama 4", "Ironwood TPU", "SO-101"],
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 30, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🧠 OpenAI shipped reasoning models that finally use the whole toolbox\n\nThe industry has spent a year saying agents matter. OpenAI decided to attach tools to the reasoning tier and call everyone's bluff.\n\n- **What launched:** OpenAI released o3 and o4-mini on April 16, 2025, saying both models can use ChatGPT tools agentically, including web search, Python, file analysis, image understanding, and image generation.\n- **What it bragged about:** OpenAI says o4-mini became its best benchmarked model on AIME 2024 and 2025, reaching 99.5% pass@1 with Python, while o3 cut major real-world task errors by 20% versus o1 in expert evaluations.\n\n*Reasoning models now come with hands, not just opinions.*\n\n**Sources:** [Introducing OpenAI o3 and o4-mini](https://openai.com/index/introducing-o3-and-o4-mini/) | [OpenAI o3 and o4-mini System Card](https://cdn.openai.com/pdf/2221c875-02dc-4789-800b-e7758f3722c1/o3-and-o4-mini-system-card.pdf)\n\n---\n\n## 💻 GPT-4.1 arrived with a million-token appetite and a coding complex\n\nApparently the new baseline for model launches is \"bigger context, better diffs, lower price.\" Very relaxing pace.\n\n- **The release:** OpenAI launched GPT-4.1, GPT-4.1 mini, and GPT-4.1 nano on April 14, 2025, with up to 1 million tokens of context and a refreshed June 2024 knowledge cutoff.\n- **The performance pitch:** OpenAI says GPT-4.1 scored 54.6% on SWE-bench Verified, up 21.4 points over GPT-4o, and priced the flagship at $2 per million input tokens and $8 per million output tokens.\n\n*The API market remains a benchmark arms race with invoices attached.*\n\n**Sources:** [Introducing GPT-4.1 in the API](https://openai.com/index/gpt-4-1//) | [GPT-4.1 model docs](https://platform.openai.com/docs/models/gpt-4.1)\n\n---\n\n## 🦙 Meta dropped Llama 4 and called openness a product strategy again\n\nNothing says calm confidence like releasing flagship models on a weekend and immediately comparing them to everyone else.\n\n- **What Meta released:** Meta introduced Llama 4 Scout and Llama 4 Maverick on April 5, 2025 as native multimodal mixture-of-experts models, both with 17 billion active parameters, while keeping Behemoth as the still-training teacher model.\n- **What matters:** Meta says Scout can fit on a single H100 with Int4 quantization, Maverick uses 128 experts, and both were made available the same day via Llama.com and Hugging Face.\n\n*Open model strategy now looks a lot like \"ship the weights and dare the market to keep up.\"*\n\n**Sources:** [Llama 4 models announcement](https://about.fb.com/br/news/2025/04/modelos-llama-4/) | [Meta AI with Llama 4](https://www.meta.ai/)\n\n---\n\n## ⚙️ Google unveiled Ironwood because inference has become its own arms industry\n\nTraining was the prestige project. Inference is where the power bill moved in and unpacked.\n\n- **The hardware move:** Google Cloud announced Ironwood on April 9, 2025 as its seventh-generation TPU and first TPU designed specifically for large-scale inference.\n- **The scale claim:** Google says Ironwood delivers more than 10x the peak performance of its latest high-performance TPU generation, and in a separate launch post described it as offering 5x more peak compute capacity and 6x the HBM of Trillium.\n\n*The model war is now a datacenter architecture contest with branding.*\n\n**Sources:** [Introducing Ironwood TPUs and new innovations in AI Hypercomputer](https://cloud.google.com/blog/products/compute/whats-new-with-ai-hypercomputer) | [Ironwood TPU overview](https://cloud.google.com/resources/ironwood-tpu-interest?e=48754805&hl=en)\n\n---\n\n## 🦾 Hugging Face kept pushing cheap robotics instead of waiting for a grand manifesto\n\nWhile everyone else is still promising general robots, Hugging Face is out here shipping better hobbyist arms and cleaner tooling.\n\n- **The robotics update:** Hugging Face's LeRobot v0.5.0 consolidated SO-100 and SO-101 support into one codebase, added bi-manual setups, and expanded hardware support through CAN bus motors and new robot integrations.\n- **The hardware angle:** Hugging Face's SO-101 documentation positions the arm as its flagship robot platform, while TechCrunch reported on April 28, 2025 that the 3D-printable arm starts around $100.\n\n*Physical AI remains suspiciously grounded when the bill of materials is public.*\n\n**Sources:** [LeRobot v0.5.0](https://huggingface.co/blog/lerobot-release-v050) | [SO-101 documentation](https://huggingface.co/docs/lerobot/en/so101)\n"
  }
